AGI - In 70 AD Heaven moved from Jerusalem to Rome. Clear sign of the transfer "celeste" was the well-marked of God ravaged by the Roman general Titus to the Hebrew bureaucrats, > then carved on the homonymous Arco at the Capitoline Forum. The leader drank that he destroyed Solomon's temple and defeated the riots on Earth. But the treasure on which he put his hands was worth much more than his pride. It is said that the spoils were part of objects that were the sacred genesis of the Semitic people.
&nbsp;
For example, the Ark of the Covenant with the Tables of Law and the Candelabro of Gold a> seven arms (the Menorah), as many as are the days of creation. According to the prescriptions of the Holy Scriptures, the Ark was an acacia wood case, inside and outside covered with pure gold and containing the Tables which the Lord wrote with fire and handed to Moses on Mount Sinai. According to tradition, even the Candelabro had been forged on order and indications of Heaven. It was the result of a single precious metal casting > (about 35 kilos) and the arms were fed with the same oil (expression of the relationship between divine and human represented by numbers 3 and 4).
&nbsp;
In Rome, a year after the military campaign, there are those who tell that the commander demanded those trophies by parade on the Sacred Way, at Palatino>. A passage that is still seen today in bas-reliefs on the Arch of Titus, the Arch of God inaugurated in 81. Symbols aside, the general's enterprises were the unknowing carriers of a “celeste” force that was re-placing the pieces on the religious chessboard. A real divine storm causes an epochal change that, as always, was more clear to posteriors than to contemporaries.
&nbsp;
The capital of monotheism (Jerusalem)> saw its fading primacy, while a new Creed (Christianity) became sharper and moved the center of faith from the Middle East to the West, to Rome. How was that possible? The birth of Christ was like the shining of a new Sun on men. The crucifixion of the Nazarene > did not grasp Christianity, but gave him voice and power so strong that he oversaw the empire and give a different sense of march to history, even mocking. For example, in 67 in Rome the apostles Peter and Paul were killed > and years after the same city decided to celebrate them as patron saints >, every year and the day before it was to celebrate Romulus and Remo, on June 29. And again, Christianity had been considered an arcinemic of the Roman Lupa, and yet in 313 it was liberalized by Emperor Constantine and, in 380, with successor Theodosius became even state religion.
&nbsp;
And the Golden Candle?> The lyrics say that in 455 he disappeared with the sack of Rome of the Vandals of Genserico, or that the Menorah ended in the dungeons of the Lateran, or thrown at the bottom of the Tiber, sought by a boat that would have crossed the river in the long and wide and eventually would have sunk. In the early nineteenth century, someone had even opened a company specialized in hunting lost treasures, but failed and closed its doors, like the dream of finding the Menorah.

